SIMPLE: protestant
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Protestant
<hw>Prot"es*tant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>protestant</ets>, fr. L. <ets>protestans</ets>, <ets>-antis</ets>,
p. pr. of <ets>protestare</ets>. See <er>Protest</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>One who protests; -- originally applied to
those who adhered to Luther, and protested against, or made a solemn
declaration of dissent from, a decree of the Emperor Charles V. and the
Diet of Spires, in 1529, against the Reformers, and appealed to a
general council; -- now used in a popular sense to designate any
Christian who does not belong to the Roman Catholic or the Greek
Church.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1153 --></p>

<p><ent>Protestant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Protestant
<hw>Prot"es*tant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>protestant</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Making a protest;
protesting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to the faith and practice of those
Christians who reject the authority of the Roman Catholic Church;
<as>as, <ex>Protestant</ex> writers</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Protestantical</ent>⟦br⟧
